    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, thanks. I see a section here about \"indemnification\" too. It basically says I'm responsible for any losses or legal fees if I breach the agreement. Are there any specific risks or \"hidden\" dangers I should be looking out for in that kind of clause?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Indemnification clauses in contracts are indeed important to understand, as they can have significant implications for your responsibilities and potential liabilities. Essentially, an indemnification clause requires one party to compensate the other for certain losses or damages, which can include legal fees, court costs, and other expenses incurred due to a breach of the agreement.\n\nWhile indemnification clauses are common and can be beneficial in protecting the interests of both parties, there are a few risks and \"hidden\" dangers to be aware of:\n\n1. Broad Scope: Indemnification clauses can sometimes be written in a very broad manner, potentially covering a wide range of scenarios. This can leave you open to unexpected liabilities. It's important to carefully review the specific language of the clause to understand the extent of your obligations.\n\n2. Unlimited Liability: Some indemnification clauses may require you to cover all losses, regardless of their size or whether they were caused by your negligence or the other party's actions. This could potentially expose you to significant financial risk.\n\n3. Third-Party Claims: Indemnification clauses may also require you to defend against claims made by third parties. This can be particularly challenging if you are not the direct party involved in the dispute.\n\n4. Legal Costs: In addition to covering losses",
      "source": "target",
      "gen_token_ids": [
        1993,
        133678,
        3166,
        99572,
        306,
        28735,
        553,
        22476,
